  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":57,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":340,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":340,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed — conversational pace, no pressure to hit a number yet. Let your body wake up gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":47,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into your easy aerobic zone. Breathing should be comfortable enough to hold a full conversation. Heart rate should sit well below threshold — think 65-75% max HR.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off gradually in the final 5 minutes. Walk the last 1-2 minutes if it feels good.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at a very gentle jog for the first 5 minutes — no watch-watching, just feel.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2-3 minutes after stopping. A few light calf raises can be a good habit given your Achilles history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday is your aerobic foundation day — easy, honest effort. With 12 years of experience you already know what 'easy' feels like, and this week is a maintenance week sitting right around 55 km, so there's no need to push. The goal here is blood flow, aerobic stimulus, and keeping the body moving after the weekend long run. Easy runs are where most of your long-term fitness is built — this one counts.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Interval Tempo\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":62,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":340,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog warmup — 15 minutes at your easy pace. Include 4-6 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes if your legs feel ready.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval at threshold pace (4:28/km). Comfortably hard — you should be able to speak in short phrases but not full sentences. This is lactate threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy float recovery — keep moving, don't stop. This 2-minute recovery is intentionally short to keep lactate elevated and maximize threshold adaptation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval. Try to match the effort of the first — pace should feel the same, not harder. If it feels significantly harder, ease off 5 sec/km.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy float recovery. Check in with your left Achilles — any unusual tightness? Note it but don't panic.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third and final cruise interval. Controlled finish — finish strong but not racing. The last rep should feel like a 7/10 effort, not a 9/10.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":19,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog cooldown back to your starting point. Let your heart rate come down naturally over 15-20 minutes.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging before the first threshold interval. Don't skip this — cold threshold work is a fast track to injury, especially with your Achilles history.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15-20 minutes easy jog cooldown. Do your standard calf stretching routine afterwards, and consider 2-3 minutes of gentle Achilles mobilization.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Tuesday is your primary quality session this week — 3 x 8-minute cruise intervals at threshold pace (4:28/km) with 2-minute easy recoveries. Cruise intervals are the backbone of marathon fitness maintenance. They keep your lactate threshold sharp without the accumulated fatigue of a continuous tempo run. The 2-minute recoveries are short by design — this is a Daniels-style cruise interval structure that keeps lactate in a productive zone. Total threshold stress is 24 minutes, which is appropriate for your fitness level and maintenance goal. The surrounding easy running brings this workout to roughly 12 km total.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gentle start — you may feel Tuesday's tempo in your legs. That's normal and expected. No pressure.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the slower end of your easy range today (5:56/km or even a touch slower if needed). Wednesday is a true recovery day in disguise — it's about moving without adding meaningful stress. HR should be 60-70% max.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 2-3 minutes. Consider doing a short yoga or mobility routine after this run — hips, calves, and Achilles especially.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Go by feel today. If the legs feel heavy from Tuesday, that's exactly right. Start slower than you think you need to.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Gentle calf stretches and Achilles mobilization recommended.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is an honest easy day — a buffer between Tuesday's quality work and Thursday's intervals. Running easy the day after a threshold session isn't just recovery, it actively promotes the aerobic adaptations from the day before by maintaining blood flow and clearing metabolic byproducts. Aim for the slower end of your easy range (5:44-5:56/km). This run should feel almost embarrassingly easy — that's the right sensation. 9 km keeps the week's volume on track without adding fatigue.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Track Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":11,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":340,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15-minute easy warmup jog. Include 6 x 20-second strides with full recovery in the final 4 minutes — this primes your neuromuscular system for the faster work ahead.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1000m (approximately 4:11/km pace). Each rep should feel hard but controlled — a 8/10 effort. You should finish each rep feeling like you could have done 10-15 more seconds, not like you're dying. This is honest VO2max work, not racing. Take 3 minutes easy jog between each rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy jog recovery between each interval. Keep moving — don't stop and walk unless something feels wrong. Active recovery keeps blood flowing and prepares you for the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":13,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 10-15 minute cooldown jog. Walk the final 2-3 minutes. This is not optional — it helps your body begin the adaptation process immediately.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Full 15-minute warmup jog plus strides before the first interval. VO2max work on cold legs is ineffective and increases injury risk.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15-minute easy cooldown jog, then walk 3 minutes. Check in with your left Achilles — any unusual tightness after the faster work should be noted and monitored.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday's session targets your VO2max — the ceiling of your aerobic capacity. For a maintenance goal, including one VO2max session per week keeps your aerobic ceiling from dropping while you're not in a build phase. Five 1000m repeats at 4:11/km (your interval pace from VDOT 46.7) with 3-minute jog recoveries is a classic, evidence-based structure. The total quality volume is 5 km at interval pace, which is well within appropriate limits. One important note: given your Achilles history, the faster pace on Thursday warrants extra attention to your warmup and how the tendon responds post-run. If there's any unusual tightness, flag it early.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 2-minute walk if your legs feel particularly heavy from Thursday. No rush.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"True recovery pace — slower end of easy range (5:50-6:00/km is perfectly fine today). The goal is active recovery, not fitness building. HR should stay comfortably low.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 3 minutes. Spend 10 minutes on mobility work after — hips, calves, Achilles especially before tomorrow's rest day.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk 2 minutes before jogging. There's no 'too slow' today.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3-5 minutes. This is a good day for a longer mobility or foam rolling session — invest in Sunday's long run by taking care of your body today.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday is your active recovery day — short, slow, and deliberate. After two quality sessions this week (Tuesday tempo + Thursday intervals), your body needs genuine recovery before Sunday's long run. 7 km at an honest easy pace keeps the legs moving without adding meaningful stress. Think of this as preparation for Sunday, not a workout in its own right. If your legs feel genuinely fatigued or your Achilles feels off, this is also a day where substituting a 30-40 minute easy bike ride or swim is a completely valid option.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Rest or Optional Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Complete rest is the preferred option today. If you feel energetic and well-recovered, 30-40 minutes of low-impact cross-training (easy cycling, swimming, or yoga) is fine. Nothing that stresses the legs meaningfully.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. If doing cross-training, ease in gently for the first 5 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"If cross-training, cool down easily for 5 minutes and do your standard mobility routine. Spend extra time on calf and Achilles care today — Sunday's long run is tomorrow.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is a true rest or very light day — the final preparation before Sunday's long run. Rest is not the absence of training; it's the process through which adaptation actually happens. Your body gets fitter during recovery, not during the run itself. With two quality sessions and four running days already this week, Saturday's rest is one of the most productive things you can do for Sunday's long run. If you're the type who struggles with full rest days, a gentle 30-40 minute yoga session or easy swim is a great outlet.\",\"perceived_effort\":1},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Sunday Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":108,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":340,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":283,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 5 minutes very gentle — don't look at your watch. Just move. Your body will find its rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":78,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":340,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Kilometres 1-15 at easy pace (5:22-5:44/km). This is the aerobic foundation of the long run. Stay genuinely easy — don't let the fresh legs push you faster than this. Conversational pace throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":283,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4-5 km at marathon pace (4:43/km). This is the key stimulus of this long run — finishing at goal marathon pace teaches your body to run economically when fatigued. It should feel controlled and strong, not desperate. If it feels easy, that's great. If it feels hard, ease back slightly — the easy kilometres before this matter more.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 1 km easy jog, then walk 3-5 minutes. Don't stop abruptly after the marathon pace finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No separate warmup needed — the first 5 km of the run serves as your warmup. Start conservatively.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Rehydrate and refuel within 30-45 minutes. Gentle stretching — calves, quads, hips. Pay attention to how your left Achilles feels and note anything unusual.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the cornerstone of your week — 20 km with the final 4-5 km at marathon pace (4:43/km). This structure is a classic progression long run, and it serves a specific purpose: it teaches your body to run at marathon pace when already aerobically fatigued, which is precisely the state you'll be in during a race. For a maintenance goal, 20 km keeps your long run fitness intact without adding excessive fatigue. The marathon pace finish adds quality without turning this into a workout — the first 15 km are genuinely easy and protect your recovery. Your training history shows you've been running 18-21 km long runs consistently, so 20 km is well within your established range. One gentle reminder: given your Achilles history, pay attention to how it responds as the run gets longer. If there's any unusual tightness past 15 km, it's okay to ease the pace finish — protecting the tendon is always the smarter long-term decision.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
  "finishReason": "stop",
